AB  - It is shown that in a two-sector production model with uncertainty, analogous to work of Batra and Sakai, there exists an implicit, and arbitrarily restricted, stock market interpretation of the model and that the appropriate duality lies between the relation of factor endowments and equity outputs and the relation of factor prices and equity prices. These observations permit a generalization of the Batra-Sakai assumption of maximization of expected utility of profits. This is accompanied by an extensive characterization of the implicit market and several of its comparative-statics properties. A 2 × 2 × 2 × 2 joint-production formulation is developed to examine stability properties.
