AB  - The paper utilizes the overlapping generations framework to derive demand functions for money and capital. We show that many of the macroeconomic comparisons of alternative exchange regimes are not legitimate since changing the exchange regime alters the portfolio rules of rational agents. One cannot simply postulate a set of asset demand equations and then hold various income, interest rate, and wealth elasticities constant when the exchange regime changes. Having derived the demands for money and capital from optimizing behavior, we show how changing the exchange regime affects expected capital holdings and expected utility levels of optimizing agents.
